-----------------------------------------Post 1------------------------------------------------

Wyoming leads anonymous incorporations in the US, OpenCorporates data shows

New Limited Liability Companies, preferred for privacy and asset protection, reached a new high in Wyoming in 2023 and surpassed Delaware, which had historically been on top.

2023: Wyoming outdoes Delaware in incorporations' rate

Last year, the Cowboy State recorded a historical 42% increase in incorporations, up to 378 per 1,000 adults.

Registrations of new companies in Wyoming have tripled in the past five years, shows a recent analysis of OpenCorporates database, in its aim of making company data open, transparent, and accessible to all.

The majority of these incorporations are Limited Liability Companies (LLC), which pay no taxes in Wyoming, enjoy some of the strongest asset protections, and are easy to set up from anywhere in the world. Currently, 75% of all companies registered in Wyoming are LLCs.

For many years, Delaware was the indisputable destination for new entities and it is still the domicile of over 67% of Fortune 500 companies, according to Delaware’s Division of Corporations.

But in 2023, Wyoming surpassed Delaware for the first time with 378 new companies per 1,000 adults. The average of new companies created last year in the rest of the US was 11, not including Puerto Rico.

While in Delaware, the growth of LLC ran in parallel with the rise of other types of companies, in Wyoming this has not been the case.

Wyoming LLCs: an unparalleled rise in the last decade

Not only in Wyoming have LLC outnumbered other company types. When summing up overall numbers in every state, LLC are the preferred option for new companies, and Wyoming has played a role in this.

LLC have overtaken other company types across the US

Summing up annual incorporations in each state, the proportion of new Limited Liability Companies has increased by 12% over the past decade.

-----------------------------------------Post 2------------------------------------------------

How Wyoming LLC became so popular?

While Wyoming has attracted new LLC, other types of companies have not gained the same popularity and have remained at levels similar to the average of other states. This has led to an abnormally high number of LLC per 1,000 adults in the Cowboy State.

Wyoming is the least populated state in the US, with less than 600,000 residents. It's a small market and mining still plays an important role in its economy. So how come that 166,960 entities chose to start a new business there in 2023, 92% of them LLC?

At OpenCorporates, in our mission to make corporate data more transparent and accessible to all, we have analysed our own database to bring some light to this trend.

12 times more new Wyoming LLC compared to average

A bit of history

Wyoming was, in fact, the birthplace of LLC in 1977. In the early days it was considered a mix between a limited partnership and corporation. And so its taxation wasn't clear, until a 1988 IRS judgment ruled that LLC should to be taxed as limited partnerships. This was to the model's advantage, as limited partnerships carry only half the tax burden compared to corporations.

The result was a small business entity model providing owners with personal liability protection while offering flexibility in management and taxation. In the next decades, LLC became popular not just in Wyoming but across the country, and not just for small businesses but for a wide range of purposes.

In 2010, the New Wyoming LLC Act enhanced privacy protections for members and managers. They also allowed for the creation of multiple LLCs under a single entity. On top of that, it provided charging order protection, which shields the LLC and its assets from immediate claims by creditors “to a greater extent than permitted in most jurisdictions,” according to legislative advisers.

In parallel, by 2011 Wyoming had adopted about 100 amendments to the state’s trust laws. A decade before, in 2003, the state had adopted the Uniform Trust Code (UTC), like most jurisdictions. However, Wyoming went several steps further in terms of protection from creditors and flexibility for self-settled trusts.

The combination of Wyoming LLC and trust laws has created what is known as the Cowboy Cocktail, “a double-barreled approach to asset protection“ only found in Wyoming, as described by the Washington Post.

Timeline: Law changes in the 2010s were followed by LLC growth

In 2016, LLC incorporations took off in Wyoming with an increase of over 30%. Could the appeal of the Cowboy Cocktail have contributed to this remarkable rise?

Additionally, the reforms in the early 2010 coincided with the raising popularity of online company formation services and e-commerce, which enable people to establish LLCs in Wyoming from abroad and to sell products on the internet. While the advantages of Wyoming LLCs are tied to their operations within the state, in the digital world clients can be located anywhere. This allows e-commerce businesses to deliver products worldwide. As long as they maintain their operations within Wyoming, they don’t risk incurring fines.

In recent years, Wyoming has been trying hard to become the crypto hub par excellence in the US, with the adoption of about 30 new crypto-friendly or crypto-permissive laws since 2019. In March this year, the state passed a law for Decentralized Autonomous Organizations (DAOs), which sets them apart from other types of companies, such as LLCs. The state is also preparing to become the first state to have a state-backed cryptocurrency.

Selling points

If one is to believe advertising, one could argue that privacy is the main attraction of setting up a LLC in Wyoming.

Source: Google Ad Transparency Centre, Meta Ad Library

Other advantages are a quick and non expensive set-up, possibility to set LLC from abroad and adequacy for online business.

-----------------------------------------Post 3------------------------------------------------

TK Registered agents

TK TK

Singular locations

Sheridan is a small town four hours away from Mount Rushmore and home to about 19,000 people. There’s a place with this name in over twenty states, but only in Sheridan, Wyoming there are 320,308 LLCs registered. This means that there are 16 times more LLCs than residents of all ages.



Most LLCs in Sheridan, up to 96%, are registered at one of two addresses. Nothing in the appearance of the buildings suggests that they are home to thousands of companies.


Wyoming connection

If you buy one of Trump’s watches, it will be shipped to you, if all goes well, from a company named TheBestWatchesonEarth LLC. This company, established by the end of July, is registered at one of the two popular addresses in Sheridan: 1309 Coffeen Avenue.

The organizer of this entity, according to OpenCorporates data, is Andrew Pierce. Formerly a Caribbean business developer, he is the founding partner, along with Mark Pierce, of Wyoming Trust and LLC Attorney, formally known as Cloud Peak Law Group, which is also registered at 1309 Coffeen Avenue. On their website, they briefly describe the history of the family business: “What was the most difficult hurdle? Estate taxes and divorces.”

This is not the first collaboration between Pierce and the former president. In February, they launched Trump Sneakers, licensed under the business name 45footwear LLC. Andrew Pierce is listed as the organizer, with Cloud Peak serving as the registered agent, similar to the arrangement for Trump’s watches. The company was set up just some weeks before the sneakers were advertised. The sneakers, sold as a limited edition for $399 a pair, quickly sold out. Months later, 45footwear LLC filed a federal lawsuit against online merchants selling counterfeits and sought millions of dollars in damages.

Cloud Peak Law Group serves as the agent of 61,398 LLCs in Wyoming, according to OpenCorporates' database. This means that the company has facilitated the formation of that many entities. Interestingly, a company with the same name is also registered in New Castle, Delaware.

-----------------------------------------Post 4------------------------------------------------

TK Consequences

TK TK

Shell companies

In the aftermath of the Panama Papers, many included Delaware in the list of tax havens, typically located in small countries.

LLC is not a synonym for dodgy business, but its protection of secrecy makes it very difficult to track illicit activities. A disproportionate number of LLCs per adult capita can signal the presence of shell companies, according to the EU Tax Observatory, an independent research laboratory.

Shell companies have little or no operations in the place where they are officially located. “Instead, they exist primarily as entities on paper, used for transactions and asset holding, generally to exploit regulations, create opaque ownership structures, or reduce tax obligations,” says the research organisation.

Cryptocurrency and cyberattacks

The ease and anonymity of Wyoming LLCs seem to be attracting cybercriminals as well. In September last year, the International Press Institute (IPI) website was taken down shortly after the organisation reported on how cyberattacks were threatening Hungarian independent outlets. Reuters linked this event, along with a handful other high-profile hacks, to Wyoming LLCs.
